{"pageProps":{"note":{"id":"e8m9ox1ixcc2hu8sren4lj4","title":"Why React Query","desc":"","updated":1654695431082,"created":1654495824743,"custom":{},"fname":"cs.webdev.frontend.language.js.jsframework.react.state-management.tools.react-query.why-react-query","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":"vault"},"contentHash":"a8642bc8f396ed22a5d6074dc0e76bfe","links":[{"type":"wiki","from":{"fname":"cs.webdev.frontend.language.js.jsframework.react.state-management.tools.react-query.why-react-query","id":"e8m9ox1ixcc2hu8sren4lj4","vaultName":"vault"},"value":"cs.webdev.frontend.language.js.jsframework.react.state-management.types-of-application-state.server-state.requirements","alias":"Requirements","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":164,"offset":418},"end":{"line":4,"column":299,"offset":553},"indent":[]},"xvault":false,"sameFile":false,"to":{"fname":"cs.webdev.frontend.language.js.jsframework.react.state-management.types-of-application-state.server-state.requirements"}}],"anchors":{},"children":[],"parent":"8co83flzdjcijmu4u26giwn","data":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"why-react-query\">Why React Query<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#why-react-query\"></a></h1>\n<p>When it comes to managing state, people usually prefer a global state management systems like Redux or MobX. These libraries can work, however,they introduce more problems treating the server state the same as the client state and using a global store.</p>\n<p>What we need is a library that takes care specifically of the server state, something that handles errors, loads the server state and handles all the server state <a href=\"/Personal-Knowledge-Vault/notes/fo7ae2wgrgcipwtbhfqag8b\">Requirements</a>.</p>\n<p> React Query solves all of them - most of them automatically! And even though React Query ships with sensible defaults, pretty much every aspect of how it fetches, stores, and delivers your server state can be configured.</p>","noteIndex":{"id":"2rzu5qtc4erc8gkfiteeysj","title":"Ro